title: Numerical Data
text:
Central Tendency
Central tendency is a statistical concept that refers to the central or typical value around which a set of data points tends to cluster. It is used to summarize and describe a data set by identifying a single representative value that provides insights into the data’s overall characteristics.

title: Numerical Data
text:
Variation
Variation in statistics refers to the extent to which data points in a dataset deviate or differ from a central tendency measure. Understanding variation is crucial for making informed decisions, drawing meaningful conclusions, and assessing the reliability of statistical analyses.

Quartiles
Quartiles are three values (Q1, Q2, Q3) that divides the data into four subsets.

title: Numerical Data

Q1 is the value signifying that a quarter of the data is lower than it.

title: Numerical Data

Q2 - Median
Q2 is the value signifying that half of the data is below it.

The median also represents the central tendency of the data.

title: Numerical Data

Q3
Q3 is the value signifying that 3 quarters of the data is below it.

title: Numerical Data
text:
Mean
The mean is another measurement for central tendency.
\[
\bar X = \frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{i=1}X_i
\]

\(n\): total data points
\(X_i\): data points
\(i\): indexing data
\(\sum\): add all from first (bottom) to last (up)

title: Numerical Data
text:
Variance
The variance is a measurement on the average squared distance the data points are from the central tendency.
\[
s^2 = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum^n_{i=1}(X_i-\bar X)^2
\]

title: Numerical Data
text:
Standard Deviation
The standard deviation is a measurement on the average distance the data points are from the central tendency.
\[
s=\sqrt{s^2}
\]

title: Numerical Data
text:
Outliers
These are data points that seem to be highly distant from all other variables.

Histogram
A histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution or frequency of data points in a dataset. It provides a visual way to understand the shape, central tendency, and spread of a dataset by dividing the data into intervals or bins and showing how many data points fall into each bin as a bar.

\]

title: Data Visualization
text:
Proportional Tables
A proportion table is a type of statistical table used to display the relative frequencies or proportions of different categories within a dataset. It provides a way to represent the distribution of data in terms of percentages or proportions, making it easier to compare and understand the relative sizes of different categories.

text:
Pie Charts
A pie chart is a circular graphical representation used to display data in a way that illustrates the relative proportions or percentages of different categories or components within a whole. Pie charts are particularly useful for showing the composition of a dataset when you want to emphasize the parts of a whole and how they relate to each other.

Experimental studies are research designs in which the researcher deliberately manipulates one or more independent variables to observe their effects on an outcome of interest. Observational Studies
Observational studies are research designs in which researchers observe and collect data on individuals or groups without intervening or manipulating any variables. These studies aim to understand and describe the relationships between variables or to analyze the natural occurrence of events or phenomena. Unlike experimental studies, observational studies do not involve the manipulation of independent variables, and they are often used when it is not ethical or practical to conduct experiments.

In order to run these large language models, companies need to use a large amounts of energy. This is because large servers are needed to both train and execute a model.

We must be conscious consumers and demand more from these companies to provide safe working conditions and livable wages.

Sampling
Sampling is the process of selecting units from a population interest to collect data from.

title: Data Summarization
text:
Sampling
When Sampling you want to maintain these properties:

Representative sample
Large enough sample size

title: Data Summarization
text:
Sampling Example
We want to answer the question, are people happy?

title: Data Summarization
text:
Random Sampling
When sampling, we strive for random sampling

Each unit in the population of interest must have an equal probability of being selected for the study.
This ensures a representative population

title: Data Summarization
text:
Independent Sampling
In addition to random sampling, we strive to make sure each unit is independent from each other.

The probability of UNIT A being sampled will not affect the probability of UNIT B to be sampled.

title: Data Summarization
text:
Sampling Variation

Random samples may vary from the population of interest.
Due to randomness, samples many not look the or biased.
However, this is to be expected as because the sample will not be biased in one way or another.
Samples are then considered unbiased as long as experimental units were collected randomly.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
MLR
Multivariable Linear Regression (MLR) is used to model an outcome variable (\(Y\)) by multiple predictor variables (\(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_p\)).

Using MLR, you propose that the ouctome variable was constructed from a set of predictors, with their corresponding regression coefficients (\(\beta\)), and a bit of error


\[
Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p + \varepsilon
\]
\[
\varepsilon \sim DGP
\]

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Model Data
\[
Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p + \varepsilon
\]
\[
\varepsilon \sim DGP
\]

\[
Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \beta_2 X_{i2} + \cdots + \beta_p X_{ip} + \varepsilon_i
\]
\[
\varepsilon_i \sim DGP
\]

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Unknown Parameters
\[
Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \beta_2 X_{i2} + \cdots + \beta_p X_{ip} + \varepsilon_i
\]

\[
\beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_3, \ldots, \beta_p
\]

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Estimated Model
\[
Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \beta_2 X_{i2} + \cdots + \beta_p X_{ip} + \varepsilon_i
\]
\[
\hat Y_i = \hat\beta_0 + \hat\beta_1 X_{i1} + \hat\beta_2 X_{i2} + \cdots + \hat\beta_p X_{ip}
\]

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Estimating Prameters
\(\beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_3, \ldots, \beta_p\) are estimated by minimizing the following function:
\[
\sum^n_{i=1} (Y_i-\hat Y_i)^2
\]

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
\(\hat \beta_i\) Representation
Each regression coefficient \(\beta_i\) represents how the predictor variable changes the outcome, as it increase by 1 unit.

For categorical dummy variables, the \(\beta_i\) represents how the outcome will change when the data point belongs to that value.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
\(\hat \beta_i\) Interpretation
For \(hat \beta_i\), which is the regression coefficient (slope) of \(X_i\):
As \(X_i\) increases by 1 unit, the outcome (\(Y\)) will increase/decrease by \(\hat \beta_i\) units, adjusting for all other predictor variables.

For categorical dummy variables \(X_i\):
The outcome \(Y_i\) increases/decreases by \(\beta_i\) units for category \(X_i\) compared to the reference category, adjusting for all other predictor variables.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Intepreting Minor coefficient
\[
dance = 0.54 + 0.07 Minor + 0.18 valence - 0.06 energy
\] Minor song’s average danceability score is 0.07 units higher compared to Major song’s, adjusting for valence and energy.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Intepreting valence coefficient
\[
dance = 0.54 + 0.07Minor + 0.18  valence - 0.06 energy
\]
As valence increases by 1 unit, danceability increases by an average of 0.18 units, adjusting for energy and type of song.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Intepreting energy coefficient
\[
dance = 0.54 + 0.07 Minor + 0.18 valence - 0.06 energy
\]
As energy increases by 1 unit, danceability decreases by an average of 0.06 units, adjusting for valence and type of song.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
\(R^2\)
Computing \(R^2\) is done by determining how much the variation in the outcome is explained by model and divided by the variation of the outcome.
\[
R^2 = \frac{\text{variation explained by model}}{\text{variation from outcome}} \\
= 1-\frac{\text{variation of residuals}}{\text{variation from outcome}}
\]

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
\(R^2\)
Problems arise when multiple predictors are added to the model. As a new predictor is added to the model, new information is added to the model which will always reduce the variation in the residuals. Therefore, the \(R^2\) will always increase.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Problems with \(R^2\) in MLR
When the number of variables increase, the regular \(R²\) will be biased in its prediction capability when new data is obtained.

Therefore, statisticians uses the adjusted \(R^2\), that penalizes the model when more variables are added. This ensures that a variable added will have a significant effect in predicting outcomes.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Adjusted \(R^2\)
\[
R_a^2 = 1-\frac{\text{variation of residuals}}{\text{variation from outcome}}\times \frac{n-1}{n-k-1}
\]

\(n\): Number of data points
\(k\): Number of predictor variables in the model

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Adjusted \(R^2\) in R


Code
xlm <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2 + ... + Xp, data = DATA)
ar2(xlm)

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Example


Code
xlm <- lm(danceability ~ mode_name + valence + energy, 
   data = taylor_album_songs)
ar2(xlm)


#> [1] 0.09275039


9% of the variation in danceability is explained by the model.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Model Selection
Model Selection is the process of obtaining a “final” model containing all the necessary predictors, and eliminating any that are not necessary.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Forward Selection
Begin with the null model (\(Y\sim 1\)) and add variables until a final model is chosen.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Backward Selection
Begin with the full model, and remove variable until the final model is chosen.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
Hybrid Selection
A hybrid approach between the forward and backward building approach.

title: Multivariable Linear Regression
text:
About Model Selection
Generally, it is not a good idea to conduct model selection. The predictor variables in your model should be guided by a literature review that illustrates important predictor variables in a model.

title: Confidence Intervals
text:
Bootstrapping Techniques
Bootstrapping is a technique to determine which \(\beta_1\) values, or any other statistic, will not be significantly different than \(b_1\).

Bootstrapping will simulate several fake data sets from the DGP of the data. Afterwards, each data set will produce a statistic to construct the sampling distribution.

title: Confidence Intervals
text:
Bootstrap Theory

The data set was generated from a distribution called \(f\).


\(f\) is unknown, we will sample from \(\hat f\) generated from the data.


When \(n \rightarrow \infty\), then \(\hat f\rightarrow f\)


So long as \(n\) is sufficiently large, the DGP of a statistic will be generated.

title: Confidence Intervals
text:
Bootstrapping Algorithm

Resample the data set using the resample() function
Fit a linear model using the resampled data and lm() function
Store the estimates from the linear model
Repeat steps 1-3, until you a high number of simulations
Compute the confidence interval or standard errors from the bootstrap estimates

title: Confidence Intervals
text:
Bootstrapping in R
The resample() will create a new data set by sampling the old data set with replacement.


Code
boot1 <- lm(weight ~ mage, data = resample(births14))
b1(boot1)


#> [1] 0.0218


Use the do() function to repeat this process a high number of times.


Code
boot_samples <- do(1000) * b1(lm(weight ~ mage, 
                              data = resample(births14)))
boot_samples %>% head()


#>        b1
#> 1 0.02027
#> 2 0.02403
#> 3 0.01389
#> 4 0.00732
#> 5 0.01881
#> 6 0.01301

\]

\[
Pr\left(t_{a/2,n-1} < \frac{b_1-\beta_1}{SE(b_1)} < t_{1-a/2,n-1}\right) = 1 - \alpha
\]

\[

\]

\[
b_1 \pm t_{a/2,n-1} SE(b_1)
\]

title: Linear Regression
text:
Linear Model
\[
\hat Y_i = \hat \beta_0 + \hat\beta_1 D_{1i} + \hat\beta_2 D_{2i}
\]

\(\hat \beta_1\) indicates how body mass changes from Adelie to Chinstrap.


\(\hat \beta_2\) indicates how body mass changes from Adelie to Gentoo.


\(\hat \beta_0\) represents the baseline level, in this case the body mass of Adelie.

title: Linear Regression
text:
Correlation
Correlation is a statistics that can be used to describe the strength of the relationship between 2 continuous variables.

\[
r = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum^n_{i=1}\frac{x_i - \bar x}{s_x}\frac{y_i - \bar y}{s_y}
\]

\(\bar x\), \(\bar y\): sample means
\(s_x\), \(s_y\): sample standard deviations



\[
-1 \leq r \leq 1
\]

text:

From IMS 2e

title: Linear Regression
text:
Coefficient of Determination
The coefficient of determination evaluates the strength between an outcome \(Y\) and the linear model, which includes \(X\).

\[
R^2 = r^2
\]


\[
0 \leq R^2 \leq 1
\]


The coefficient of determination measures the total variation explained by the linear model. The closer to 1, the better the linear model.

Pie charts are useful methods to show how a categories are related to each other in a sample.

df_pie <- cat_stats(DATA$VARIABLE, pie = TRUE)
ggplot(df_pie, aes(cat = Category, val = n, fill = Category)) +
  geom_pie()
